Numeral Systems (by base)

Binary (base-2) — uses 0, 1 → e.g., 1010 = 10
Octal (base-8) — uses 0–7 → e.g., 12 = 10
Decimal (base-10) — the everyday system, uses 0–9
Hexadecimal (base-16) — uses 0–9 and A–F → e.g., FF = 255
Base-64 — used in encoding (not strictly a number system, but common in computing)

Historical / Cultural Systems

Roman numerals 
Arabic-Indic 
Chinese numerals
Greek numerals 
Egyptian hieroglyphic numerals

Number Types (mathematical)

Integer — whole numbers, e.g., -3, 0, 42
Float / Decimal — e.g., 3.14
Fraction / Rational — e.g., 3/4
Scientific notation — e.g., 1.5 × 10⁶
Complex numbers — e.g., 3 + 4i

Formatting / Display Conventions

Locale-based — 1,000.50 (US) vs 1.000,50 (Europe)
Currency — $1,000.00, €1.000,00
Percentage — 75%
Ordinal — 1st, 2nd, 3rd...
Words — "one thousand", "forty-two"
Signed — +42, -42
Zero-padded — 007, 0042

Computing-Specific

Fixed-point — precise decimal position, used in finance
Floating-point — IEEE 754 (how computers store decimals)
BCD (Binary-Coded Decimal) — each digit stored separately in binary
Two's complement — how negative integers are stored in binary